english:
  title: A Refutation of Buddhist Doctrine on Causality
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Someone asked: "Your refutation of the Buddhist doctrine of rebirth is thorough, yet you say that all beings—human and non-human—receive their life from the qi of yin, yang, and the five elements. Among humans, we observe differences in wisdom and foolishness, virtue and vice, wealth and poverty, high and low station, long and short lifespans. Among creatures, some serve humans in labor and suffering without complaint until death; others cannot escape nets and hooks; still others, great and small, strong and weak, devour one another. When Heaven creates all things, it grants them equally, so how can there be such disparity and inequality? If we reason thus, does not the Buddhist teaching that 'all good and evil deeds committed in life receive their retribution' hold true? And is their doctrine not sound when they call deeds the 'cause' and retribution the 'effect'?"

    I replied: "I have already explained in detail above the principle by which humans and all things continually arise. Understanding this, the doctrine of rebirth refutes itself. And when rebirth is refuted, the doctrine of causality becomes clear without need for further argument. Yet since you have raised the question, how can I not return to its roots and speak again?

    Yin, yang, and the five elements interact and move in endless flux, uneven and discordant. Their qi thus manifests differences in permeability and obstruction, regularity and irregularity, clarity and turbidity, thickness and thinness, height and lowness, length and shortness. When humans and creatures are born, they arrive at particular times and receive particular configurations of qi. Those receiving the regular and permeable become human; those receiving the irregular and obstructed become creatures. Thus the distinction between noble and base arises.

    Among humans themselves: those receiving clarity become wise and virtuous; those receiving turbidity become foolish and deficient. The thick prosper; the thin suffer poverty. The high achieve rank; the low remain humble. The long-lived enjoy years; the short-lived meet early death. Such is the general pattern. The same holds for creatures. The qilin, dragon, and phoenix possess spiritual excellence; tigers, wolves, and serpents bear poison; the parasol tree, cinnamon, lingzhi fungus, and orchid bring auspiciousness; certain toxic plants bring bitterness. All these arise from the irregular and obstructed configurations of the five elements, manifesting different natures. Yet none are intentionally made thus. The *Book of Changes* says: 'The Way of Heaven transforms; each thing rectifies its nature and destiny.' The ancient sages said: 'Heaven's Way lacks intent, yet it universally pervades all things.'

    Consider divination and medicine—humble arts, yet instructive. The diviner determines a person's fortune and misfortune by tracing the waxing and waning of the five elements, saying: 'This person receives Wood as destiny; in spring they flourish, in autumn they decline. Their form is green and elongated; their heart is compassionate and benevolent.' Another receives Metal: 'Auspicious in autumn, inauspicious in summer; their form is white and angular; their heart is forceful and clear.' Water, Fire—all follow this pattern. Even ugliness of appearance and cruelty of mind stem from unbalanced endowment of the five elements.

    When physicians diagnose illness, they likewise trace it to the interaction of the five elements, saying: 'This person's cold ailment stems from kidney-water; that person's heat-ailment stems from heart-fire.' They prescribe medicine by temperature and flavor—warm, cool, cold, hot; sour, salty, sweet, bitter—distributing these among yin, yang, and the five elements, and harmony is achieved without fail. Our Confucian teaching that 'humans and creatures receive life from the qi of yin, yang, and five elements' is clearly verified and beyond doubt.

    If the Buddhist teaching were true, then human fortune and illness would have nothing to do with yin, yang, and five elements, but arise entirely from karmic retribution. Yet not a single person abandons our Confucian teaching to determine fortune or diagnose illness by Buddhist causality. Their doctrine is absurd and false, unworthy of credence. Do you still cling to it?

    Let me offer a simple, accessible comparison. In brewing liquor, the amount of yeast and koji, the firing of the vessel, the season and temperature—when these align properly, the taste becomes excellent. Too much koji brings bitterness; too much yeast brings sweetness; too much water brings blandness. Even when the ingredients combine correctly, if the vessel's firing is improper or the timing and temperature fail to match, the liquor becomes flawed. By the quality of the taste, there come distinctions of grade. The sediment is cast into filthy ground and trampled underfoot.

    Thus the liquor becomes excellent or poor, superior or inferior, useful or discarded—all from the natural convergence of circumstances. Does this too follow karmic retribution? Though this comparison is humble and commonplace, it illuminates the matter completely. The interaction and flux of yin, yang, and the five elements, proceeding in uneven dissonance, generates the ten thousand variations of beings. Its principle is likewise.

    The sage establishes teaching to transform students' material nature toward sagehood. The sage-ruler transforms decline into order and peace. Thus the sage redirects the qi of yin and yang to share in the creative work of Heaven and Earth. How could the Buddhist doctrine of causality operate in this realm?"
